Challenge: Implement Proper Accessible Names for Next and Previous Month Buttons

03
On this page
  1. Current Month Button Markup
  2. 🛠 Challenge: Set Accessible Names for Screen Reader Announcements
  3. 🛠️ Solution: Implement Proper Accessible Names for Next and Previous Month Buttons
    1. The Sub-Optimal Solution aria-hidden
    2. Adding an Accessible Name with aria-label

For this challenge, we’re going back to the date picker on the Listing Detail page.

The date picker includes < and > characters as visual indicators that the buttons will allow you to move to the previous or next months.

While it does make sense visually, you might recall that when the screen reader announced these buttons it read out “less than” and “greater than” along with the month names. This doesn’t provide a good experience for a non-sighted screen reader user.

Current Month Button Markup

Here’s what the markup for the month selection buttons currently looks like:

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<header>
  <button
    className="btn-month btn-prev"
    disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
    onClick={setPrevMonth}
  >
    <span></span>
    { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
  </button>
  <h4>{ dayjs(activeDate).format("MMMM YYYY") }</h4>
  <button
    className="btn-month btn-next"
    onClick={setNextMonth}
  >
    { dayjs(activeDate).add(1, 'month').format("MMM") }
    <span></span>
  </button>
</header>
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<header>
  <button
    className="btn-month btn-prev"
    disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
    onClick={setPrevMonth}
  >
    <span></span>
    { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
  </button>
  <h4>{ dayjs(activeDate).format("MMMM YYYY") }</h4>
  <button
    className="btn-month btn-next"
    onClick={setNextMonth}
  >
    { dayjs(activeDate).add(1, 'month').format("MMM") }
    <span></span>
  </button>
</header>

The month names are generated with help from the day.js library.

Based on the current date, day.js will subtract (or add) a month and format it as a shortened version of the month’s name. Surrounding the expression in curly braces tells React to format it and render in the button:

// Create a short month string of the previous month
{ dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
// Create a short month string of the previous month
{ dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }

The < and > symbols are added to the empty <span> tags inside the buttons with some help from CSS:

// excerpt from date-picker.scss

&.btn-prev span:before {
		content: '<';
		margin-right: 0.25em;
}

&.btn-next span:after {
		content: ' >';
		margin-left: 0.25em;
}
// excerpt from date-picker.scss

&.btn-prev span:before {
		content: '<';
		margin-right: 0.25em;
}

&.btn-next span:after {
		content: ' >';
		margin-left: 0.25em;
}

🛠 Challenge: Set Accessible Names for Screen Reader Announcements

Your challenge is to expose an accessible names for the next and previous month buttons that will give proper context to a screen reader user.

Draw upon the techniques we’ve used so far in the workshop and check your work in a screen reader.

🛠️ Solution: Implement Proper Accessible Names for Next and Previous Month Buttons

We have a couple of options for adding accessible names to these buttons.

The Sub-Optimal Solution aria-hidden

It’s worth pointing out that one way to make the screen reader announcement more user friendly is to use aria-hidden to hide the span containing the decorative symbol from the screen reader all together.

Making this code change to the previous month button looks like this:

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<button
    className="btn-month btn-prev"
    disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
    onClick={setPrevMonth}
>
    <span aria-hidden="true"></span>
    { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
</button>
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<button
    className="btn-month btn-prev"
    disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
    onClick={setPrevMonth}
>
    <span aria-hidden="true"></span>
    { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
</button>

When the button is rendered with aria-hidden applied, it does indeed remove the less-than symbol from the accessible name:

This makes for a better screen reader experience since the visual symbol won’t be announced. However, this is a sub-par solution since there’s now a lack of context that the month button is associated with moving to the previous month.

Besides, the challenge was to implement an accessible name that would lead to a better screen reader experience!

Adding an Accessible Name with aria-label

We’re going to add an aria-label to the button that will use a template literal to say “Previous month” in addition to the month’s name.

Since the Day.js string to get the name of the month already exists, we can copy it and adjust the format to MMMM to give us the full name of the month.

Here’s what the aria-label looks like added to the previous month button:

<button
		aria-label={`Previous month ${dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMMM")}`}
		...
<button
		aria-label={`Previous month ${dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMMM")}`}
		...

Follow the same process for the next month button.

Checking our work in the browser, we can see that the labels have been applied as expected:

A sighted user will still have the visual benefit of < and > to provide context, while screen reader users benefit from more descriptive announcements.

Depending on the visual and interaction design of your application, strategically including visual cues and more contextual announcements for your different users can be an appropriate technique to implement. It is still worth considering if a 1-to-1 experience can be created for all users, though. It can really help to keep things simple.
